"Dan, I told you literally one minute ago that making snap judgements are bad. And now look."

((I don't understand what she's talking about any more.))

"But you don't like the game."

"Fine. You're right. I don't." She sighs. "Honestly? Disliking it makes me feel old#footnote 22#. Resistant to change. I feel like an antibody of civilization. Rejecting the new." A pause. "There is a fine balance to strike in order to use the game without becoming addicted to the game. Without forgetting why we are here in the first place. Dan, I have to take breaks. I only play the Game maybe once, twice a week. And after I stop? I can't focus. I'm jittery. I try to sit down and read something - and I can't. My eyes move across the page but I'm thinking about my mystery. The game trains you to want excitement. It takes me a few days to reset. I know I'm back to normal when I pull out some David Foster Wallace and don't immediately lose track of what's going on."

She continues. "But most people don't stop playing. The game creates its own consumers. Viewing VeraGames' stupid product placement and banner ands and most importantly? Consuming entertainment."

